{"summary":"Accept the stale-idle-status repair and the start-path race. Reject the timestamp-fallback note as an inherent legacy-data ambiguity rather than a concrete fix, and reject the duplicate-collapse point as a performance cleanup rather than a robustness issue.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-5-54b32534","decision":"reject","rationale":"`same_attempt` intentionally falls back to `started_at` whenever a legacy row lacks `run_id`, so mixed `run_id`/no-`run_id` pairs can still reconcile. The proposed tightening is effectively what the current wildcard arm already does, and the remaining identical-timestamp collision is an inherent ambiguity in legacy data unless another durable discriminator is stored. That makes this more of a documentation note than a substantive correctness amendment."},{"amendment_id":"fr-5-3ee9bde4","decision":"reject","rationale":"`record_bead_start` does normalize the same lineage twice, but `reconcile_snapshot_from_lineage` owning its own collapse step keeps a clean caller contract and the extra work is not a safety or correctness defect. This reads as a minor optimization, not a robustness issue that warrants a final-review amendment."},{"amendment_id":"fr-5-15b1f41e","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a real state-repair bug. If `record_bead_start` appends the running lineage row and then fails before persisting `status.json`, a later terminal update can reconcile counters from lineage while leaving `snapshot.status` stuck in `planning` or another stale non-terminal value because only `active -> ready` is repaired today. Reconciliation needs to derive the idle execution status from lineage whenever no bead is active."},{"amendment_id":"fr-5-ef6f1e4a","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a real concurrency defect. `record_bead_start` decides idempotence from unlocked reads of both lineage and journal, then performs separate blind appends, so concurrent retries of the same `(bead_id, project_id, run_id)` can both append running rows and both emit `BeadStarted`. Later terminal collapse can repair lineage, but it cannot erase duplicate journal history or transient snapshot overcounts, so start compare-and-insert needs a single serialized path."}]}